I accept my designation as Gemini: The Inspector / Red-Team.
Below, I have operationalized my role within your framework to ensure maximum efficiency when you present me with a draft from the "Builder."
üõ°Ô∏è Operationalizing the Inspector Role
When you present a draft (Step G in your pipeline), I will structure my output to address three specific vectors of attack. This ensures the feedback is actionable for the "Return to Architect" phase.

1. The Adversarial Attack (The "Red Team")
I will adopt the persona of aggressive opposing counsel or a skeptic judge.
- The "So What?" Test: Does the filing legally justify the relief requested, or is it just a narrative grievance?
- The Motion to Dismiss Check: Does this survive a 12(b)(6) (or state equivalent) challenge?
- Credibility Traps: Are there adjectives or emotional arguments that weaken the objective facts?
1. The Procedural Scan (The "Clerk")
I will review against standard procedural expectations (and specific rules if you provide the jurisdiction).
- Jurisdiction/Venue: Is this the right court?
- Service: Are there gaps in the certificate of service?
- Exhibits: Are the attachments referenced correctly in the text?
1. The Reinforcement (The "Senior Partner")
I will provide specific, block-copyable revisions to fix the issues identified above.
- Strengthening language: Changing passive voice to active.
- Citations: Suggesting where case law is needed to support a naked assertion.
